  "prompt": "Why does whisky help toothache, what is the medical explanation for this?",
  "response": "Whisky can provide temporary relief from toothache through several mechanisms:\n\n1. Numbing effect\n- Alcohol acts as a local anesthetic\n- It temporarily numbs nerve endings, reducing pain sensation\n- The high alcohol content (around 40%) creates a brief analgesic effect\n\n2. Antiseptic properties\n- Alcohol has antibacterial properties\n- Can help kill bacteria around the painful tooth or gum area\n- Reduces potential infection risks\n\n3. Vasoconstrictive action\n- Alcohol causes blood vessels to constrict\n- This can help reduce inflammation and swelling\n- Reduces blood flow to the affected area, potentially lessening pain\n\n4. Disinfectant qualities\n- Can help clean the affected area\n- Reduces bacterial presence that might be causing infection\n\n5. Mild sedative effect\n- Alcohol can have a mild sedative impact\n- Helps reduce overall pain perception and anxiety\n\nImportant caveats:\n- This is a temporary solution\n- Does not treat underlying dental problems\n- Professional dental care is essential for persistent tooth pain\n- Excessive alcohol use can actually harm oral health\n\nWhile whisky can provide short-term relief, it's not a substitute for professional dental treatment.",
